### [Exercise](#grpue) {#ue06_2}

## `across()`: Processing Multiple Variables {#across}

A highly versatile addition to `mutate()` and `summarise()` is `across()`. This allows us to apply a function to multiple columns simultaneously, without repeating code:




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
dat3 %>%
  summarise(studs = mean(studs),
            profs = mean(profs))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
     studs  profs
1 21690.62 328.25
```


:::
:::




Here, `across()` offers a much shorter syntax for variable selection, and we can use [`?select_helpers`](02_intro.qmd#selecthelpers) like `matches()`:




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
dat3 %>%
  summarise(across(.cols = matches("studs|profs"),.fns = ~mean(.x)))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
     studs  profs
1 21690.62 328.25
```


:::
:::




This is also compatible with `.by=`:



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
dat3 %>%
  summarise(across(matches("studs|profs"), ~mean(.x)), .by= prom_recht)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
  prom_recht   studs profs
1       TRUE 20082.0   290
2      FALSE 26516.5   443
```


:::
:::




We can apply multiple functions by placing them in a `list()`:



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
dat3 %>%
  summarise(across(matches("studs|profs"), list(mean = ~mean(.x), sd = ~sd(.x))), .by= prom_recht)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
  prom_recht studs_mean studs_sd profs_mean profs_sd
1       TRUE    20082.0 14857.84        290 183.2081
2      FALSE    26516.5 16351.84        443 272.9432
```


:::
:::




You can define this `list()` in advance and use it later:



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
wert_liste <- list(MEAN = ~mean(.x), SD = ~sd(.x))

dat3 %>%
  summarise(across(matches("studs|profs"), wert_liste), .by= prom_recht)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
  prom_recht studs_MEAN studs_SD profs_MEAN profs_SD
1       TRUE    20082.0 14857.84        290 183.2081
2      FALSE    26516.5 16351.84        443 272.9432
```


:::
:::




The `.names()` argument allows us to control the naming of columns. `{.fn}` stands for the function being applied, and `{.col}` represents the name of the variable being processed.




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
dat3 %>%
  summarise(across(matches("studs|profs"), 
                   wert_liste,
                   .names = "{.fn}_{.col}"),
            .by= prom_recht)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
  prom_recht MEAN_studs SD_studs MEAN_profs SD_profs
1       TRUE    20082.0 14857.84        290 183.2081
2      FALSE    26516.5 16351.84        443 272.9432
```


:::
:::




All these functions also work with `mutate()`:




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
dat3 %>%
  mutate(across(matches("studs|profs"),
                wert_liste, 
                .names = "{.col}XX{.fn}"))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
  studs profs gegr prom_recht                uni studsXXMEAN studsXXSD
1 19173   322 1971       TRUE         Uni Bremen    21690.62  14309.16
2  5333    67 1830       TRUE         Uni Vechta    21690.62  14309.16
3 15643   210 1973       TRUE      Uni Oldenburg    21690.62  14309.16
4 14954   250 1971      FALSE          FH Aachen    21690.62  14309.16
5 47269   553 1870       TRUE        RWTH Aachen    21690.62  14309.16
6 23659   438 1457       TRUE       Uni Freiburg    21690.62  14309.16
7  9415   150 1818       TRUE           Uni Bonn    21690.62  14309.16
8 38079   636 1995      FALSE FH Bonn-Rhein-Sieg    21690.62  14309.16
  profsXXMEAN profsXXSD
1      328.25  199.0827
2      328.25  199.0827
3      328.25  199.0827
4      328.25  199.0827
5      328.25  199.0827
6      328.25  199.0827
7      328.25  199.0827
8      328.25  199.0827
```


:::
:::




[More examples in the across() documentation](https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/reference/across.html)

